Urea itself has a high melting point (133°C) due to strong hydrogen bonding. The N,N-dimethyl groups generally raise the melting point due to an increase in the molecular weight. However, these groups are also electron-donating, which can disrupt the planarity of the aromatic ring-urea system to some extent and reduce the melting point compared to urea itself. But overall, since the urea group's influence is significant, it will have a dominating contribution to the elevation of the melting point.
